= lesson 15: with and like

In lesson 8, we learned three prepositions: #strong[ůĪ•© tawa], #strong[ůĪ§¨ lon],
#strong[ůĪ•ß tan], which are all about location and direction. Toki Pona actually
has two more prepositions:

#list((
  word("ůĪ§ô", "kepeken", "using, by means of"),
  word("ůĪ•Ė", "sama", "similar to, same as"),
))

Let's learn a few more words that go well with these prepositions:

#list((
  word("ůĪ§Ü", "ante", "to change; different, other"),
  word("ůĪ•Č", "pali", "to work, to build"),
  word("ůĪ•ľ", "leko", "brick, block"),
))

Remember, prepositions start prepositional phrases:

#list((
  word("ůĪ•ĖůĪ•ě", "sama sina", "same as you"),
  word("ůĪ§ôůĪ•¨", "kepeken toki", "by means of language"),
  word("ůĪ§ôůĪ§éůĪ§Ü", "kepeken ilo ante", "with a different tool"),
))

And those phrases then go either on the end of a sentence:

#list((
  sentence("ůĪ§īůĪ•¨ůĪ•ĖůĪ•ě", "mi toki sama sina.", "I speak like you."),
  sentence(
    "ůĪ§īůĪ•ČůĪ§ČůĪ•ľůĪ§ôůĪ§é",
    "mi pali e leko kepeken ilo.",
    "I make bricks using a tool.",
  ),
))

Or in place of the verb itself:

#list((
  sentence("ůĪ•ÜůĪ§ßůĪ•ĖůĪ•ě", "ona li sama sina.", "They are like you."),
  sentence("ůĪ•ÜůĪ§ßůĪ§ôůĪ§é", "ona li kepeken ilo.", "They use a tool."),
))

== Moving a house

Now that you know all five prepositions: #strong[ůĪ•© tawa], #strong[ůĪ§¨ lon],
#strong[ůĪ•ß tan], #strong[ůĪ§ô kepeken], and #strong[ůĪ•Ė sama], here's something new
about them: these can all be regular nouns, verbs, or adjectives!

#list((
  word("ůĪ•©", "tawa", "to move; movement; moving"),
  word("ůĪ§¨", "lon", "true, real, existing"),
  word("ůĪ•ß", "tan", "cause, origin"),
  word("ůĪ§ô", "kepeken", "usage"),
  word("ůĪ•Ė", "sama", "similar, alike"),
))

Some of them, like #strong[ůĪ•© tawa], #strong[ůĪ§¨ lon], are used this way very
frequently. Others, like #strong[ůĪ•ß tan] and #strong[ůĪ§ô kepeken], quite rarely.
Let's look at some examples:

#list((
  sentence("ůĪ•°ůĪ§īůĪ§ßůĪ•Ė", "sona mi li sama.", "My knowledge is similar."),
  sentence(
    "ůĪ•¨ůĪ•ěůĪ§ßůĪ§¨",
    "toki sina li lon.",
    "Your speech is real.
(What you're saying is true.)",
  ),
  sentence(
    "ůĪ§īůĪ•∑ůĪ§ģůĪ§ČůĪ•†ůĪ•©",
    "mi wile lukin e sitelen tawa.",
    "I want to watch a moving picture. (a video, a film)",
  ),
  sentence("ůĪ§īůĪ•°ůĪ§āůĪ§ČůĪ•ß", "mi sona ala e tan.", "I don't know the reason."),
))

We often like to shape sentences in such a way that it's impossible to misread
these as "prepositions" --- notice how there's no phrase immediately after them!

Sometimes you can make very similar sentences, except one has a verb like
#strong[ůĪ•© tawa] or #strong[ůĪ§¨ lon], and the other has a preposition #strong[ůĪ•©
  tawa] or #strong[ůĪ§¨ lon]! Make sure not to confuse these pairs:

#list((
  sentence(
    "ůĪ§ĎůĪ§ßůĪ•©ůĪ•≠",
    "jan li tawa tomo.",
    "Someone goes to the house. (preposition)",
  ),
  sentence("ůĪ§ĎůĪ§ßůĪ•©ůĪ§ČůĪ•≠", "jan li tawa e tomo.", "Someone moves the house. (verb)"),
  sentence("ůĪ§īůĪ§¨ůĪ§į", "mi lon ma.", "I'm on land. (preposition)"),
  sentence(
    "ůĪ§īůĪ§¨ůĪ§ČůĪ§į",
    "mi lon e ma.",
    "I summon land into reality.
I establish a territory. (verb)",
  ),
))
